definition.value: A province of Indonesia on the western end of the island of New Guinea. It covers the Bird's Head (or Doberai) Peninsula and surrounding islands. West Papua was created from the western portion of Papua province in 2003-02, initially under the name of Irian Jaya Barat, and was renamed Papua Barat (West Papua) on 2007-0207.
The capital and largest city of Antigua and Barbuda, a country located in the West Indies in the Caribbean Sea.
A large beach resort located across parts of two Jamaican parishes, Westmoreland and Hanover.
The territorial capital of the Netherlands Antilles. Located on the island of Curacao.
A province of Panama. The capital is the city of Bocas del Toro, found on the island of Colon. Its area is 8,745 km2 and it is formed by 9 principal islands.
A populated place. A city in the Province of Bocas del Toro of the Republic of Panama.
A populated place. A city.

The capital city of North Korea, located on the Taedong River. The city was split from the South P'yongan province in 1946. It is administered as a Directly Governed City (Chikhalsi), on the same level as provincial governments.
South Korea's second largest metropolis. Busan is located on the Southeastern tip of the Korean Peninsula.

A province in the centre of South Korea. It was formed in 1896 from the northeastern half of the former Chungcheong province. The provincial capital is Cheongju. The province is part of the Hoseo region, and is bounded on the west by Chungcheongnam-do province, on the north by Gyeonggi-do and Gangwon-do provinces, on the south by Jeollabuk-do province, and on the east by Gyeongsangbuk-do. Chungcheongbuk-do is the only land-locked province in South Korea. The province is mostly mountainous, dominated by the Noryeong Mountains to the north and the Sobaek Mountains to the east.

A province of South Korea, with its capital at Chuncheon. Gangwon-do is bounded on the west by Gyeonggi-do province, on the south by the provinces of Chungcheongbuk-do and Gyeongsangbuk-do, and on the east by the Sea of Japan. To the north lies the province's North Korean counterpart, Kangwon province.

A province of South Korea. Seoul is located in the heart of the province, but has been separately administered as a provincial-level Special City since 1946. Gyeonggi-do is located in the northwest of South Korea. The province is bounded on the east by Gangwon-do, on the south by Chungcheongbuk-do and Chungcheongnam-do, and on the west by Incheon and the Yellow Sea. The province almost completely surrounds Seoul. To the north lies Kaesong Industrial Region and North Hwanghae Province in North Korea.

A province in eastern South Korea. It is bounded on the east by the Sea of Japan (East Sea), on the south by Gyeongsangnam Province, on the west by Jeollabuk and Chungcheongbuk Provinces, and on the north by Gangwon Province.
A metropolitan city and a major seaport on the west coast of South Korea, near Seoul.

A province in the southwest of South Korea, formed in 1896 from the southern half of the former Jeolla province, remained a province of Korea until the country's division in 1945, then became part of South Korea.

The fourth largest city in South Korea. It is the capital of Gyeongsangbuk-do province, although it is not legally part of that province. Daegu sits in a basin surrounded by low mountains. Palgongsan to the north, Biseulsan to the south, the foothills of Gayasan to the west, and a series of smaller hills in the east.

A designated metropolitan city under the direct control of the central government's Home Minister. The city was also the capital of South Jeolla Province until the provincial office moved to the southern village of Namak in Muan County in 2005.
A city located in the south-central region of Cambodia, at the confluence of the Tonle Sap, Mekong, and Bassac rivers.
A province of Indonesia, located at the western end of Java Island.
A city on the northern coast of Central Java, Indonesia.

The smallest province of Indonesia (excluding Jakarta). It is located on the island of Java. It is the only province in Indonesia that is still formally governed by a precolonial Sultanate. Yogyakarta is located in south-central Java. It is surrounded by the province of Central Java (Jawa Tengah) and the Indian Ocean in the south.

A province of Indonesia. It is located on the eastern part of the island of Java and also includes neighboring Madura and Bawean islands.

The second largest city in East Java province, Indonesia.

A populated place. A city in Banten, Indonesia. It is located about 20 km west of Jakarta.
The capital of the Purwakarta Regency of West Java, Indonesia.
A populated place. A city in southeastern West Java, Indonesia, between Bandung and Purwokerto on the southerly of the two major road routes across Java.
A populated place. A town in Distrik Nabire, Nabire Regency, Papua Province.
A special territory (daerah istimewa) of Indonesia, located on the northern tip of the island of Sumatra.

A province of Indonesia, which includes two main islands, Bangka and Belitung, and several smaller ones that lie from the east of Sumatra to the northeast of South Sumatra province. The Bangka Strait separates Sumatra and Bangka, and the Gaspar Strait separates Bangka and Belitung. The South China Sea is to the north, the Java Sea is to the south, and Borneo to the east is separated from Belitung by the Karimata Strait. The province was formerly part of South Sumatra, but became a separate province along with Banten and Gorontalo in 2000.

A province of Indonesia. It is on the southwest coast of the island of Sumatra, and borders the provinces of West Sumatra, Jambi, South Sumatra and Lampung. The capital and largest city of the province is Bengkulu city.
A province of Indonesia, located on the southern tip of the island of Sumatra. It borders the provinces of Bengkulu and South Sumatra.

A province of Indonesia, located in the center of Sumatra island along the Strait of Malacca. The provincial capital and largest city is Pekanbaru. The Riau Islands were part of Riau until 2004, when they were made into a separate province.
A province of Indonesia located on the east coast of central Sumatra. The capital of the province is Jambi city.
A populated place. A city in North Sumatra, Indonesia.
